<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-05-24T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-05-24T10:00:00-05:00" n="1231" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1231">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.142/1602</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SWG1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-05-24T15:00:00+00:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">May 24, 1916, 3 p. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 8 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1412. Your 1486, April 27. Foreign Office replies that Ministry of
                                Marine regrets that very serious military reasons which prevented
                                acquiescing to American Government’s previous request of a like
                                nature already explained (see my telegram 1344,<note n="2" xml:id="d1231fn2">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_927">p.
                                    927</ref>.</note> April 4, 7 p. m.) apply equally to a vessel
                                coming out of a blockaded port and returning immediately, as such
                                trip would allow a reconnaissance from <pb facs="1216" n="930" xml:id="pg_930"/> which the military and naval forces of the
                                powers at war with France would not fail to profit, whatever
                                dispositions might be taken by the American Government or the French
                                naval authorities.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_SWG1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sharp</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>